<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900912-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>900912-0010.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>09/12/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   A DEFICIT-REDUCTION PACT could be reached by today ortomorrow, say White House and congressional budgetnegotiators. Republicans and Democrats are converging on acompromise that would raise taxes by about $130 billion overfive years, including an energy tax, a new luxury-goods levyand higher taxes on alcoholic beverages.   ---</LP><TEXT>   The Big Board approved a limited form of &quot;off-hours&quot;trading for large investors that could begin later this year,in a move that marks a step toward 24-hour stock trading.   ---   Drexel could face a $50 million Big Board fine, followingthe exchange's request to bankruptcy court to initiatedisciplinary proceedings against the collapsed securitiesfirm.   ---   Salomon agreed to pay $83.8 million to the Department ofEnergy to settle claims stemming from a probe of allegedviolations of the govern ment's crude-oil price controls.   ---   Chase Manhattan was forced by investors' uncertainties toreset the rate on $200 million of subordinated notes to yield13.017%, up from the previous rate of 9.66% and just shy ofthe maximum permissible increase.   ---   The fund that insures bank deposits could require Treasuryassistance if a recession strikes, said the GAO. Somelawmakers urged an other boost in bank insurance rates.   ---   First City Bancorp of Texas said it is considering seekingone or more money-center banks as minority partners to shoreup the bank's finances and bolster its global standing.   ---   Philip Morris appointed William I. Campbell as presidentand chief executive of its domestic tobacco subsidiary,succeeding Ehud Houminer.   ---   A proposed accounting rule may be scaled back underpressure from banks and accounting firms. The proposal,involving debt issues, would make bank earnings morevolatile.   ---   Tenneco said its packaging unit is in talks to buy millsand timberland from Georgia-Pacific for about $740 million,extending the successful unit's pattern of acquisitions.   ---   ASK Computer agreed to buy software-maker Ingres in anunusual four-way deal, in which ASK will use funds from stockit will sell to Hewlett-Packard and GM's EDS unit.   ---   IBM will soon unveil several new computers that act asnetwork hubs, which will put it in direct rivalry withCompaq, which controls the high end of that specializedmarket.   ---   U.S. food-price inflation will be pushed up this year andnext by the Persian Gulf crisis, according to AgricultureDepartment analysts.   ---   Texas Instruments is asking Japanese semiconductor makersto pay higher royalties on a memory chip patent. The U.S.company's stock soared on news of its demand.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 113,220,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2612.62, off 2.97; transportation 909.58, up 1.48; utilities200.26, off 0.19.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3362.52, up11.59.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.39, up 0.40; spotindex 129.67, up 0.58.   Dollar: 140.30 yen, up 0.75; 1.5855 marks, up 0.0035.</TEXT></DOC>